summary:
A form of temporary facial paralysis that can cause significant facial distortion. It usually affects only one side of the face, however, in rare cases, it can affect both sides.
 &nbsp;
The exact cause of __Bell's Palsy__ isn't known, but many scientists believe that reactivation of a dormant viral infection can cause the facial nerve to swell and become inflamed. Another possible cause is reduced blood supply to the 7th cranial nerve, one of the facial nerves. __Bell's Palsy__ is the most common cause of facial paralysis.

A form of a sexually transmitted infection that affects the genitalia. 
&nbsp; 
__Genital Herpes__ is commonly caused by *Herpes Simplex virus- 2 (HSV-2)*. It can also be caused by *HSV-1*, which is the cause of oral herpes (cold sores on the mouth and lips).

When a tube behind the testicle that stores and carries sperm, called the *Epididymis*, gets inflamed.
&nbsp; 
__Epididymitis__ is usually caused by an infection. Most commonly this is from a urinary tract infection or a sexually transmitted infection, but it can also be caused by the mumps virus. There are other even rarer causes including complications of operations in the area and a medication called Amiodarone.

When a wound or scratch occurs on the surface of the *cornea* (the transparent outer surface of the eye), and usually heals completely within two or three days. However, in some cases it can lead to complications, such as ulcers of the cornea.
 &nbsp;
The most common cause of a __Corneal Abrasion__ is a scratch to the cornea caused by small objects entering the eye or getting stuck under the eyelid. In addition, contact lens wearers are at an increased risk for __Corneal Abrasions__ from the lens itself.

Inflammation of the sinuses, which are hollow air-filled pockets within the bones of the head and face.
 &nbsp;
The most common cause of __Acute Sinusitis__ is viral infection, which should go away without treatment, although bacterial infections can also occur and require antibiotics.

An inflammatory disease of the small airways of the lungs. The airways narrow, swell, and may produce extra mucus.
 &nbsp;
__Asthma__ may be caused by inherited (genetic) factors and can be influenced by environmental ones such as air pollution and allergens like dust or pollen. Respiratory infections may also play a role.

A condition in which the heart can't pump enough blood to meet the body's needs. In some cases, the heart can't fill with enough blood. In other cases, the heart can't effectively pump blood to the rest of the body. Some people have both problems.
 &nbsp;
There are many causes of __CHF__. Most commonly it is caused by coronary artery disease, heart attacks and uncontrolled high blood pressure. Rarer causes include diseases of the heart valves, heart muscle and infections.

This is an adverse reaction which occurs after an exposure to a drug, food, chemical, or another environmental factor. 
 &nbsp;
An __Allergic Reaction__ is caused by a type of *hypersensitivity reaction* when the body's immune system overreacts to substances that are normally harmless. They can range from minor skin rashes to serious life-threatening conditions. In cases with both shortness of breath and facial swelling, urgent medical attention might be required.

Pain in the chest area that comes from the muscles, cartilage or bones of the chest. It is a common cause of chest pain and does not involve the heart.
 &nbsp;
The cause of __Musculoskeletal Chest Pain__ varies, but it is often due to inflammation or irritation of the cartilage, muscles or other soft tissues of the chest wall, typically as a result of exercise or trauma.

This occurs when an area of the heart muscle doesn't get enough oxygen-rich blood. It is a type of *Angina* where symptoms occur in a regular pattern so that you can predict frequency, severity, and triggers.
 &nbsp;
__Stable Angina__ is caused by inadequate blood flow through the *coronary arteries*, which supply blood to the heart muscle.

An accumulation of pus that forms inside the teeth, gums, or bones that hold the teeth in place. 
 &nbsp;
A __Dental Abscess__ is usually caused by a bacterial infection that originated in the teeth or gums.

This is a condition with various symptoms in the hand caused by compression of the *median nerve*, which runs from the forearm into the palm of the hand and controls muscle movement and sensation in the hand and forearm. *Median nerve* compression typically occurs in the *carpal tunnel*, a narrow, rigid passageway of ligaments and bones at the base of the hand near the wrist. 
 &nbsp;
__Carpal Tunnel Syndrome__ is often caused by a combination of factors that reduce the available space for the *median nerve*, rather than a problem with the nerve itself. Contributing factors may include putting on weight, pregnancy, trauma or injury, repeated use of the hand/wrist, hormonal problems, and rheumatoid arthritis.

A blood clot that forms in a vein deep in the body. Most __DVTs__ occur in the lower leg or thigh; however, they also can occur in other parts of the body. A __DVT__ that breaks off and travels through the bloodstream can create a blockage called an *embolism*.
 &nbsp;
Some factors that can lead to __DVT__ formation are immobility, surgery, certain medications, inherited conditions, and cancers.

When a *ligament* in the neck is injured, stretched, or torn. A *ligament* is tough connective tissue that connects two bones.
 &nbsp;
__Cervical Sprain__ happens when the soft tissues of the neck are stretched abruptly, most commonly by an *acceleration-deceleration injury* during motor vehicle accidents, sports, or falls.

An injury to the ulnar nerve. The *ulnar nerve* runs through the upper arm, elbow, and wrist, supplying nerves and sensation to the muscles in the forearm and part of the hand. The most common site of nerve damage is at the elbow, followed by the wrist. 
&nbsp; 
__Ulnar Nerve Neuropathy__ is caused when the ulnar nerve gets entrapped or damaged. This can be caused by leaning on one's elbows and putting pressure on the nerves but can also be caused by trauma, over-use, or something else pressing on the nerve.

A condition that happens after a brain injury, often called a *concussion*. The syndrome leads to temporary neurologic changes. 
&nbsp; 
__Post-concussion Syndrome__ is caused by trauma to the head that causes a brain injury called a *concussion*. Auto accidents and sports injuries are common causes of a *concussion*.

Occurs when the bladder becomes infected and the mucous membranes that line the bladder become inflamed. Also called __Acute Cystitis__.
 &nbsp;
__Bladder Infections__ happen when bacteria gets into the *urethra* (the tube through which urine leaves the body), moves up into the bladder, and multiplies there causing symptoms.

Occurs when cells form nodules on the prostate, increasing its overall size.
 &nbsp;
Causes of __BPH__ may include hormones (such as testosterone) and the normal aging process.

An acute, spreading infection of the deep tissues of the skin and muscle that causes the skin to become warm, red and tender and may also cause fever, chills, swollen lymph nodes, and blisters.
 &nbsp;
__Cellulitis__ can develop if bacteria enter the skin through cuts or sores. If you have a weakened immune system or circulation problems, it is also easier for bacteria to enter the tissue. The infection may then reach even deeper layers of tissue, causing severe __Cellulitis__ to develop.

Also called __Tinea Pedis__, this is a fungal skin infection of the foot. The fungi are present in most people's feet but an increased 'hot' environment can encourage their growth and cause a flaky rash. The fungi most often grows between the toes, but may infect any part of the foot. 
 &nbsp;
__Athlete's Foot__ is caused by fungi that infect the skin. They can enter the skin through small cracks and grow on the top layer of skin.

An illness from eating contaminated food or drink. The infection is generally limited to the gastrointestinal tract - the intestines and stomach. 
 &nbsp;
__Acute Food Poisoning__ is caused by consuming a variety of infectious organisms or their toxins in contaminated food or drink. This *foodborne disease* typically occurs a few hours after consuming the contaminated food.

The inability to digest and absorb proteins called *gluten,* a substance found in wheat, rye, and barley. __Celiac Disease__ causes damage to the lining of the small intestine and prevents absorption of nutrients. __Celiac Disease__ is both a disease of malabsorption\u2014meaning nutrients are not absorbed properly\u2014and an abnormal immune reaction to *gluten*.
 &nbsp;
__Celiac Disease__ is genetic, meaning it runs in families. Sometimes the disease is triggered\u2014or becomes active for the first time\u2014after surgery, pregnancy, childbirth, viral infection, or severe emotional stress.

Inflammation of one or more pouches, or *diverticula*, that bulge out from the wall of the colon (the large intestine). 
 &nbsp;
The cause of both __Acute Diverticulitis__ and *diverticula* is unclear, but a low fiber diet and constipation may be factors in the development of diverticula.

An inflammation of the appendix, a small pocket of tissue normally connected to the cecum, an area of the large intestine near its junction with the small intestine. This is found below and to the right of the belly button.
 &nbsp;
__Appendicitis__ is caused by an obstruction, or blockage, of the *appendiceal lumen* (the cavity or channel within a tube or tubular organ such as a blood vessel or the intestine). Mucus backs up in the *appendiceal lumen*, causing bacteria that normally live inside the appendix to multiply. As a result, the appendix swells and becomes infected.

__Dysmenorrhea__, or __Menstrual Period Pain__, is abnormally painful abdominal cramps during menstruation. There are two types, called __Primary and Secondary Dysmenorrhea__.
 &nbsp;
__Primary Dysmenorrhea__ is caused by the womb muscle contractions alone, and is likely to involve the production of too many prostaglandins (hormones) or a particular sensitivity to them, and is common in young women. __Secondary Dysmenorrhea__ is often caused by benign (non-cancerous) growths in the womb, such as fibroids or polyps. Endometriosis, womb tissue being present in other places, can also cause severe period pain. Contraceptive coils (IUDs: intrauterine devices) used for birth control can also cause painful periods.

Depletion of fluid that disrupts the balance and volume of fluids in the body. 
 &nbsp;
__Dehydration__ is caused when the body doesn't have enough fluid volume. This can be caused by vomiting, diarrhea, bleeding, excessive sweating, decreased fluid intake, and use of certain medications.

A disorder of the inner ear that causes severe dizziness as well as hearing loss and tinnitus (noises in the ear).
&nbsp; 
The cause of __Meniere's disease__ is unclear, although the accumulation of fluid in the inner ear may play a role.

A tear in the lining of the anus. 
 &nbsp;
__Anal Fissures__ are caused by trauma to the anal canal. Common causes of injury include passing a large or hard stool, repeated episodes of diarrhea, or giving birth.

This is a way of classifying a headache that does not meet the criteria of a more specific type of headache, such as a migraine. 
&nbsp; 
The cause of __General Headaches__, by definition, has not yet been found. Often, more time or testing is needed to reach a definitive diagnosis. Sometimes headaches could be a sign of a more severe condition and require medical attention. Some of these include headaches which are extremely severe and came on suddenly, were preceded by a head trauma, accompanied by vision problems or neurological symptoms like hand, leg, or face weakness or problems speaking, or are unlike the usual headaches or migraines in people who suffer from them occasionally.

This is a group of mental health disorders characterized by anxious feelings or fear that interfere with daily activities such as job performance, school work, or relationships. They involve more than temporary worry or fear. Instead the anxiety does not go away and can get worse over time. There are several different __Anxiety Disorders__, including *generalized anxiety disorder*, *panic disorder*, and *social anxiety disorder*.
 &nbsp;
The cause of __Anxiety Disorders__ is unknown, but experts believe biological and environmental factors play a role.

A condition with recurrent *seizures*. Although classically these seizures are known for causing loss of consciousness and convulsions, they can also manifest in many other ways such as strange sensations and muscle spasms. 
 &nbsp;
__Epilepsy__ is caused by abnormal electrical activity in the brain. Often, no apparent cause for new onset epilepsy is identified, especially in young adults. However, several factors can disturb the normal pattern of brain cell activity and cause seizures. These include abnormal brain structure, stroke, brain injury and infections.

An inflammation of the liver that can cause permanent damage. The liver plays a critical role in many different body functions.
&nbsp;
__Acute Hepatitis__ may be caused by viruses, medicines, or toxins. Several different viruses, such as hepatitis A, B and C, cause __viral hepatitis__.

A group of conditions in which the heartbeat is irregular, too fast, or too slow. Also known as __Cardiac Arrhythmia__ or __Irregular Heartbeat__.
&nbsp;
__Cardiac Arrhthymia__ may be caused by many different factors, including coronary artery disease, toxins, electrolyte imbalances, injury from a heart attack, or healing process after heart surgery. Occasionally, it can occur in young, healthy people.

Cancer that develops within the breast tissue. Many different forms exist.
&nbsp;
The exact cause of __Breast Cancer__ is unclear but some risk factors are known. Among the most significant factors are advancing age and a family history of breast cancer.

Cancer that forms in the large intestine or rectum. It is one of the most common cancers worldwide. Symptoms include bowel habit changes and blood in the stool.
&nbsp;
__Colorectal Cancer__ usually begins with a benign polyp or a cluster of cells. There are also inherited genetic mutations that can increase the risk of these cancers.

A common viral infection of the mouth which results in blisters and sores forming in the mouth.
&nbsp; 
__Gingivostomatitis__ is mainly caused by the Type 1 Herpes Simplex Virus but can be caused by other viruses or bacteria.

A buildup and blockage of earwax (*Cerumen*) in the ear canal. Also known as Earwax Blockage.
&nbsp;
__Impacted Cerumen__ is most commonly caused by at-home attempts to remove earwax. Some people are prone to earwax buildup.

A chronic autoimmune, connective tissue disease affecting multiple organs and joints. Also known as __SLE or Lupus.__
&nbsp;
__Systemic Lupus Erythematosus__ is an disease where the immune system mistakenly attacks normal cells. It can run in families and affects more women than men.

A cancer of the cells in the immune system, including lymph tissue, spleen and bone marrow. There are many types including *Hodgkins* and *Non-Hodgkins*.
&nbsp;
The cause of __Lymphoma__ is unclear but risk factors include family history, immune system problems and previous cancers.

Tissue within the skull cavity that is not normal brain tissue. It can put pressure upon the brain as it grows and takes up space.
  &nbsp;
An __Intracranial Space Occupying Lesion (SOL)__ can be a tumor (benign or malignant), an abscess, or anything else taking up space in the skull cavity.

The most common form of arthritis, causing inflammatory changes to the cartilage and the bone tissue next to the cartilage. 
  &nbsp;
__Osteoarthritis__ is caused by a mixture of factors, including advancing age, obesity, severe overuse of a particular joint, joint abnormalities and genetic factors.

Inflammation of the *uvea* or middle layer of the eye.
  &nbsp;
__Uveitis__ is usually unexplained and is due to an 'autoimmune' response, meaning that the body begins to attack itself, and this can happen to people who have other 'autoimmune diseases'. It can also happen due to infections, trauma to the eye, or toxins.

A common condition characterized by breast lumps (or thickening of breast tissue) which are noncancerous. This includes *fibroadenomas* and *cysts* of the breast. 
  &nbsp;
__Local Benign Breast Condition__ is thought to be influenced by hormones, although the exact cause is unclear. The swellings may change size with the menstrual cycle.

A broad term describing a degenerative condition of the spine. It is very common and does not always cause pain. 
&nbsp;  
__Spondylosis__ is caused by years of wear and tear on the spine. It is often seen with *degenerative disc disease.*

Occurs when nerves don't function properly in people with diabetes. It typically occurs in the legs and feet, but can affect other nerves in the body as well. 
&nbsp; 
The precise cause of __Diabetic Neuropathy__ is not clear, but it may result from damage to the nerves by excess glucose (sugar) in the bloodstream.

An infectious virus, also known as __HSV__. It is spread by direct contact.
&nbsp;
__Herpes Simplex__ has two main types. Type 1 viruses usually causes cold sores on the lips or nostrils. Infections with type 2 viruses cause sores on the genitals.

An infection that is transmitted by a scratch or bite from a cat. Classically it causes painful, swollen lymph nodes near the scratch or bite. Also known as __Cat Scratch Fever__.
&nbsp;
__Cat Scratch Disease__ is caused by a bacteria spread by cats.

An inflammatory disease characterized by small nodules (or *granulomas*) of immune cells which develop in multiple organs, commonly the lungs and lymph nodes. It often resolves on its own but in rare cases can cause severe, long-term complications.
&nbsp;
The cause of __Sarcoidosis__ is unknown but the body's immune system overreacts to a trigger to form the granulomas. It does run in families.

A syndrome that happens with advanced *carcinoid* tumors, a tumor originating in the gut or lungs. The tumor produces chemicals which cause a variety of symptoms. Also called __Neuroendocrine tumor__.
&nbsp;
__Carcinoid Syndrome__ is caused by hormones produced by advanced gastrointestinal carcinoid tumors.

A group of disorders consisting of *tics*, which are sudden, atypical muscle movements which can include movements, sounds or both.
&nbsp; 
The causes of __Tic Disorders__ are unclear, although they appear to run in families.

A painless, temporary loss of vision in one or both eyes, due to lack of blood flow to the retina (back of the eye).
&nbsp;
__Amaurosis Fugax__ is not a disease but a sign of other disorders. It can occur when a blood clot blocks an artery to the retina.

Inflammation of the optic nerve, the nerve that transmits visual information from the eye to the brain. It can cause temporary visual problems and even blindness.
&nbsp;
__Optic Neuritis__ is most commonly caused by *Multiple Sclerosis* or a blood clot to the optic nerve. Other causes include infection, autoimmune disorders and methanol poisoning.

A condition where the rectum (the lower part of the intestine) slides out of place through the anus. It is rarely life-threatening but in most cases eventuallly requires surgical treatment.
&nbsp;
__Rectal Prolapse__ is caused by a weakening of the muscles and ligaments that hold the rectum in place. It occurs more commonly in people who are older than 40, have had multiple surgeries and have suffered with chronic constipation.

A kidney disorder where too much protein is excreted in the urine. Fluid retention and weight gain are common complaints.
&nbsp;
__Nephrotic Syndrome__ is caused by damage to the tiny blood vessels to the kidneys, which filter the body's blood. This can be secondary to diabetes, Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, Amyloidosis and other diseases.

A condition in which the kidneys suddenly work less well. This can result in a dangerous imbalance of fluids and salts in the body.
 &nbsp;
__Acute Kidney Injury__ can be due to numerous causes but is most commonly due to dehydration and medicines such as ibuprofen and 'ACE inhibitors'. Patients at risk of __Acute Kidney Injury__ are sometimes asked to withhold certain medicines when they are ill and at risk of dehydration.

An infection of the urethra, the tube that carries urine from the bladder out of the body.
  &nbsp;
__Urethritis__ is caused by many different organisms, including some which are sexually transmitted and others that are not.

An inflammatory condition of the skin in which lesions can appear anywhere on the body, but typically appear on the shins.
  &nbsp;
In many cases, the cause of __Erythema Nodosum__ is unknown, though it could be associated with some conditions, medications, infections and pregnancy.

A disorder marked by the thickening of skin. It can affect only the skin or spread to internal organs in addition to the skin.
&nbsp;
__Scleroderma__ is an autoimmune disease where the body's immune system mistakenly attacks normal cells. It can run in families and can be in response to exposure to silica.

A type of arthritis associated with Crohn's Disease. It affects many people with Crohn's Disease and includes arthritis in the large joints as well as pain and stiffness in the lower back.
  &nbsp;
__Crohn's Arthropathy__ is thought to be caused by a genetic component resulting in inflammation in both the gut and the joints.

A form of arthritis which affects the spine and the sacroiliac joints (where the spine attaches to the pelvis). In severe cases it can cause the spine to become fused.
  &nbsp;
The exact cause of __Ankylosing Spondylitis__ is not clear but there is a genetic component as people with a gene called HLA-B27 are at a greater risk. It also runs in families.

A chromosomal disorder in which there is an extra X chromosome resulting in a lack of the testosterone 'male' hormone. It affects to a varying degree physical and cognitive development. Also known as KS or XXY Syndrome.
  &nbsp;
__Klinefelter Syndrome__ is the result of a random genetic mutation.

A severe, life-threatening allergic reaction that occurs rapidly after exposure to an allergen. 
 &nbsp; 
__Anaphylaxis__ occurs when the body is exposed to an agent that causes the body's sudden activation of cells (called *mast cells* and *basophils*) that regulate the immune system. It is most often caused by certain foods such as peanuts, insect stings such as wasp stings, drugs, medications, or chemicals. It requires immediate emergency treatment.

Inflammation of the *pericardium*, which is the sac that surrounds the heart.
&nbsp;
In many cases, the cause of __pericarditis__ is unknown. Viral, bacterial, fungal, and other infections can result in __pericarditis__. Other possible causes include heart attack or heart surgery, other medical conditions, injuries, and certain medicines.

A form of *vasculitis*, a group of disorders that results in inflammation of blood vessels. This inflammation causes the arteries to narrow, impeding adequate blood flow. In __Temporal Arteritis__, the vessels most involved are those of the head, especially the *temporal arteries* (located on each side of the head). For this reason, the disorder is sometimes called *temporal arteritis*. However, other blood vessels can also become inflamed in __Giant Cell Arteritis__.
&nbsp;
The cause of __Giant Cell Arteritis__ is unknown.

Inflammation of the head of the penis, more common in uncircumcised males. 
&nbsp; 
__Balanitis__ can be caused by a multitude of infectious agents. Poor hygiene and morbid obesity increases the risk.

Occurs when increased pressure inside the eye damages the main nerve in the eye, *the optic nerve*, which can lead to vision loss. It is also called *narrow-angle glaucoma*.
&nbsp; 
The *anterior chamber angle* is the part of the eye that drains fluid from the eyeball. When it is clogged, fluid accumulates quickly in the eye causing the pressure inside the eye to rise rapidly and __Angle-Closure Glaucoma__ develops.

An infection of the skin and tissue between the buttocks, in what's called the *intergluteal cleft*.
&nbsp; 
A __Pilonidal Abscess__ is caused by a collection of germs and debris in the *intergluteal cleft*. Pilonidal disease often occurs in those who have a deeper gluteal cleft.

A condition in which a fertilized egg grows outside of the uterus, usually in one of the fallopian tubes. It can cause tubal rupture and/or intra-abdominal bleeding. Also known as a Tubal Pregnancy.
&nbsp;
The cause is unknown, however there are number of risk factors for an __ectopic pregnancy__, including history of ectopic pregnancy, endometriosis, tubal ligation or previous surgery on a tube, infertility, or use of an intrauterine device (IUD).
